WEBVTT

00:09.120 --> 00:11.980
Hi there, welcome to
this video where we

00:11.980 --> 00:14.140
are going to learn
about misinformation.

00:15.030 --> 00:17.180
The goal of the
presentation is to

00:17.180 --> 00:18.680
help you to
understand what

00:18.680 --> 00:21.500
misinformation is,
what motivates people

00:21.500 --> 00:26.460
to do it, and how to
recognise it. In the

00:26.460 --> 00:28.580
video, firstly, we
will look at what

00:28.580 --> 00:30.940
misinformation is,
then we will look at

00:30.940 --> 00:33.120
some examples of
misinformation and

00:33.120 --> 00:38.000
why it spreads so
easily. What is

00:38.000 --> 00:41.680
misinformation?
Misinformation is

00:41.680 --> 00:43.840
false or inaccurate
information that is

00:43.840 --> 00:46.020
spread, regardless of
whether there's an

00:46.020 --> 00:48.700
intent to deceive.
It's essentially

00:48.700 --> 00:51.000
information that
isn't true, but the

00:51.000 --> 00:53.660
person sharing it may
genuinely believe it

00:53.660 --> 00:56.600
or may not realise
it's false. This

00:56.600 --> 00:58.440
distinguishes
misinformation from

00:58.440 --> 01:00.720
disinformation, which
is false information

01:00.720 --> 01:02.820
that's deliberately
created and spread to

01:02.820 --> 01:05.420
mislead people. With
disinformation,

01:05.420 --> 01:07.940
there's intentional
deception involved.

01:10.440 --> 01:12.340
Some common examples
of misinformation

01:12.340 --> 01:14.960
include outdated
facts that were once

01:14.960 --> 01:16.760
true but are no
longer accurate,

01:16.760 --> 01:19.700
misremembered details
that get passed along

01:19.700 --> 01:22.540
, misleading
statistics taken out

01:22.540 --> 01:24.960
of context, fake news
stories shared

01:24.960 --> 01:27.220
without checking if
they are true, images

01:27.220 --> 01:29.620
or videos shared as
authentic but which

01:29.620 --> 01:31.120
have been changed.

01:35.000 --> 01:37.240
Misinformation can
spread rapidly,

01:37.240 --> 01:39.660
especially on social
media, because people

01:39.660 --> 01:41.660
often share content
without checking its

01:41.660 --> 01:44.980
accuracy. It can be
about any topic,

01:44.980 --> 01:47.860
health, politics,
science, current

01:47.860 --> 01:50.000
events, and can have
real-world

01:50.000 --> 01:52.300
consequences when
people make decisions

01:52.300 --> 01:55.280
based on false
information. The

01:55.280 --> 01:57.200
challenge with
misinformation is

01:57.200 --> 01:59.780
that it's not always
easy to identify, and

01:59.780 --> 02:01.880
correcting it can be
difficult once it's

02:01.880 --> 02:04.780
widely circulated.
People tend to

02:04.780 --> 02:07.160
remember the initial
false claim even

02:07.160 --> 02:08.800
after seeing a
correction.

